metadata.name: Fragment Assembler #100
metadata.description:
Fragment Assembler is a chaos engine that creates complex abstract patterns and textures. As the artwork is drawn, it constantly recomposes itself during assembly with a series of displacement techniques, creating new forms and visual elements, while others get broken into pieces and textures. The work is orientation agnostic, and will display the output in portrait orientation on tall displays.

Intended to display on high resolution mode. The artwork renders with lower resolution by default to maintain compatibility with lower end devices. 

Press '2' to double the internal resolution (recommended).
Press 'h' to enable full internal resolution (requires a modern desktop computer).
Press space bar to reload the work.
Press 's' to save the output as PNG.
To render a 6k PNG, first press 'h', then save with 'p' (requires a modern desktop computer).


Made with p5.js & WebGL.
Best displayed with a modern desktop system & Chrome browser. 


Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Orchard #333
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit. 

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1000x1000px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

To render a variation at a new size, open live view and append '?size=#' to the end of the URL. The new size may be from 100 to 3,000. This version will not be a 1:1 match to your edition but will have all of the same features.

metadata.name: Drone Beast synthesizer #4
metadata.description:
This is a little Drone Beast with a modular synthesizer inside. Being made of thousands of particles swarming around several attractors it reacts on different signals across the modular patch. The patch itself is based on multiple 8-bit oscillators, modulating each other and being modulated by mathematical expressions, unique for each Beast.

Press anywhere in the frame to hear the sound. Use your mouse to explore the space of drone, which is individual for each Beast. Press "a" to toggle auto-evolution.

All remaining editions (if any) will be burnt in 2 days.

@ferluht, @alexexeev, 2022

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #297
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Dynamic generations #231
metadata.description:
A classic cellular automata updates its state with a static rule based on the state of its neighbor.

This collection was created with cellular automata with an extension of that idea. Here the state and the rule are updated based on the state of its neighbor, here the rule changes in every iteration, here the rule is dynamic.

That change moves cellular automata to another level of complexity.

metadata.name: Ghrian #61
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ

metadata.name: Zee  #3
metadata.description:
As wild as it is, for me the sea has something soothing. The rushing of the waves, the strong wind in your face, the salty air, the screeching of seagulls, freezing rain. At the coast it is easy to forget everything and be in the moment. The view is expansive and no matter how ominous the clouds, somewhere the sun breaks through. 

At the same time, the raging sea can be life-threatening. Many have lost their lives at sea or by the sea, some by flooding, some in the battle for peace, others in search of a better life. 

The sea, with its many faces and stories, is beautiful, terrifying and everything in between. 

#Features
Are there birds, and if so, how many?
Is it raining?
How cloudy is it?
How rough is the sea?

Generative art coded with p5js.

metadata.name: Transmission #128
metadata.description:
GT by Ahmad Moussa || Gorilla Sun
Twitter -> @gorillasu

Notes on randomness and rarity:
This token generates a random permutation of a transmission. A transmission consists of a set of points (interceptors) that a diagonally spanned across the canvas, and connected with lines.
These interceptors can sometimes occur in a square shape.
Sometimes the signal fails to connect two dots, the amount of drops in these connections makes up the decomposition parameter.
The colored ligaments come in a variety of colors, and sometimes the entire transmission has a different color scheme. Some color schemes are extremely rare.

Notes on posting to Twitter:
To make Twitter display these correctly and not harshly compress them, they're best saved in the .jpg or .jpeg format and then posted.

metadata.name: Phaces #54
metadata.description:
Faces + Phases = Phaces. A living artwork celebrating variety and community, with a healthy dose of delayed gratification.

Each Phace starts in black and white, a simple but fascinating look at the variety that can emerge from a few lines of code. It is a sober start to an exciting journey and a reminder that good things take time.

Each week, your Phace evolves. You’ll see the next evolution every Saturday for 12 weeks, providing moments for the collector community to come together to share and celebrate the latest Phaces – there will be some wild ones in there!

Each Phace has a name, generated from a list of 144 adjectives and a 144 names randomly selected from the US census. Other features hint at the exciting evolutions to come. You know that Nonchalant Erma with Palette = Electric and Colour Boost = Wild is going to be up for a party. 

We won’t say much more, for risk of spoiling the surprises but we can’t wait to see your Phaces emerge and evolve over these coming weeks. Follow along for updates on Twitter, Insta and at https://www.phaust.art/.

------

Edition Size: 156. A tribute to the inspiration and evolution of fxHash over the 156 day beta. 

Palettes: Azure, Bioluminant, Day Glo, Electric, Lava Lamp, Livid, Peach, Peacock, Powder, Retro, Royal, Turple.

Evolutions: 12.

S: to save current Phace. All saves are at high resolution.
G: to save a grid of all revealed Phaces.
1-9, 0, E, T: to save a specific Phace – one to nine, then ten, eleven and twelve.

metadata.name: GEOMORPHISM #67
metadata.description:
A 4444 character magic spell for my rayhatching framework to render thinking rocks.

This piece may take some time to render (about 1-3 minutes, depending on hardware). The rendering time is symbolic of the vastness and agelessness of these rock structures, it is recommended to use the rendering time to contemplate deeply the concept of time spans so incredibly long, that to experience them they would have to overwrite your memories several times and thus are impossible to truly comprehend.

To ponder how, if they are so old, how come some of them float? Are these rocks the fixtures and has time and space itself eroded around them?

This project uses an approach called "rejection sampling". This means the program generates a random set of parameters, and then checks/previews how the resulting image would look. It measures the amount of visible objects, light and shadows, and then determines whether these fall into acceptable ranges. If not, it generates a new set of parameters. For certain hashes over a 100 parameter sets may be checked before it accepts the image.

The features of this project are "cliff", "ground", "thing" and "sky". These are not parameters, they are actual measurements of the resulting image, indicating what percentage of the view is occupied.

This piece can be saved as an SVG and plotted. It is recommended to run a path order optimization tool such as vpype or axicli, this will greatly reduce plotting time.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&w=.25 : The line width in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.

The line width is set to 0.25 millimetres to suit most common fine liner pen stroke widths when plotting. 

If you don't intend to plot this piece, perhaps also try rendering it at 0.2 or even 0.1 millimetres line width, for an even more detailed image (it will also take longer to render).
